1
00:00:02,436 --> 00:00:06,938
Also, with the laparoscopic
common bile duct exploration,

2
00:00:07,008 --> 00:00:11,743
post-op bile leaks and strictures
are significantly minimized.

3
00:00:11,812 --> 00:00:16,064
It was called, at the time,
an audacious technique.

4
00:00:16,132 --> 00:00:18,372
<i>And it was.</i>

5
00:00:19,269 --> 00:00:21,235
<i>Some context for you.</i>

6
00:00:21,304 --> 00:00:24,506
<i>I was the only woman in my
surgical residency program.</i>

7
00:00:24,575 --> 00:00:29,111
<i>They called me
"girl" and "Mrs. Grey."</i>

8
00:00:29,179 --> 00:00:34,616
<i>Along with the one black male
resident, I was clearly excluded.</i>

9
00:00:34,685 --> 00:00:37,318
<i>They didn't want me to
be a part of their boys' club.</i>

10
00:00:37,387 --> 00:00:39,588
<i>So I did the only
audacious thing you can do</i>

11
00:00:39,656 --> 00:00:41,022
<i>with an audacious technique.</i>

12
00:00:41,091 --> 00:00:44,526
<i>I got myself published in</i> The
Journal of American Medicine.

13
00:00:44,594 --> 00:00:47,228
<i>That caused an uproar.</i>

14
00:00:47,297 --> 00:00:52,034
<i>A resident was not first
author of a published paper.</i>

15
00:00:52,102 --> 00:00:54,769
<i>But the truly audacious
part came when they saw</i>

16
00:00:54,839 --> 00:00:59,507
<i>what I named my technique.
"The Grey Method."</i>

17
00:01:01,111 --> 00:01:02,861
<i>I put my own name on it.</i>

18
00:01:02,930 --> 00:01:05,848
<i>You should have heard
the boys roar about that.</i>

19
00:01:08,435 --> 00:01:11,569
<i>The first time I won
the Harper Avery,</i>

20
00:01:11,638 --> 00:01:15,891
<i>I dedicated it to the men
who had been so supportive.</i>

21
00:01:18,795 --> 00:01:21,830
<i>This is how my mother
wanted to be remembered.</i>

22
00:01:24,385 --> 00:01:27,853
<i>My memory of her
is a little bit different.</i>

23
00:01:27,922 --> 00:01:30,155
Where is the chief?
You're all amateurs!

24
00:01:30,207 --> 00:01:31,856
Complaining of intermittent...

25
00:01:31,925 --> 00:01:33,853
What the hell are you doing
here? Haven't I told you?

26
00:01:33,877 --> 00:01:37,117
How many times have I told you
not to bother me when I'm at work?

27
00:01:38,832 --> 00:01:41,883
<i>I'm sure everyone remembers
their own version of her.</i>

28
00:01:43,337 --> 00:01:45,520
<i>Versions I wouldn't
even recognize.</i>

29
00:01:47,408 --> 00:01:50,492
<i>It's all that's really left of
someone when they're gone.</i>

30
00:01:52,279 --> 00:01:54,045
No.

31
00:01:54,114 --> 00:01:56,014
<i>But that's the tricky thing.</i>

32
00:01:57,084 --> 00:01:58,684
Meredith.

33
00:01:58,736 --> 00:02:01,670
<i>Nobody's memory
is perfect or complete.</i>

34
00:02:01,739 --> 00:02:02,954
Mommy.

35
00:02:03,607 --> 00:02:04,722
Meredith, get up.

36
00:02:04,791 --> 00:02:06,941
<i>We jumble things up.</i>

37
00:02:08,228 --> 00:02:10,562
<i>We lose track of time.</i>

38
00:02:10,631 --> 00:02:14,699
<i>We are in one
place, then another.</i>

39
00:02:14,768 --> 00:02:18,036
<i>And it all feels like one
long, inescapable moment.</i>

40
00:02:19,623 --> 00:02:22,591
<i>It's just like my
mother used to say.</i>

41
00:02:22,660 --> 00:02:25,978
<i>"The carousel
never stops turning."</i>

42
00:02:26,046 --> 00:02:27,612
<i>I spent the day with Alex.</i>

43
00:02:27,681 --> 00:02:30,632
I needed a day,
Derek, so I took it.

44
00:02:30,701 --> 00:02:32,584
That's fine. I just
need to know why.

45
00:02:32,653 --> 00:02:33,696
No, you don't.

46
00:02:33,720 --> 00:02:35,165
You want to hear
that I cured cancer

47
00:02:35,189 --> 00:02:37,567
or that I found a vaccine
for ALS before breakfast.

48
00:02:37,591 --> 00:02:39,102
That'd be great.
Anything would be great.

49
00:02:39,126 --> 00:02:40,487
There it is again. What?

50
00:02:40,511 --> 00:02:42,221
You're waiting for me to pay up

51
00:02:42,245 --> 00:02:45,079
for this grand sacrifice
that you made for our family.

52
00:02:45,148 --> 00:02:47,343
How am I supposed to do
anything with you pressuring me

53
00:02:47,367 --> 00:02:49,912
and hovering over me for
a decision that you made?

54
00:02:49,936 --> 00:02:51,363
And you're waiting
for me to fail.

55
00:02:51,387 --> 00:02:52,720
I'm waiting for you to shine.

56
00:02:52,789 --> 00:02:55,223
Remember? That's
why you're staying here.

57
00:02:55,292 --> 00:02:58,354
And I told you, you should
go to DC and shine there.

58
00:02:58,378 --> 00:03:01,174
It was you who decided to
stay here and martyr yourself

59
00:03:01,198 --> 00:03:03,610
and now make me feel guilty
because of a decision you made.

60
00:03:03,634 --> 00:03:04,677
Well, I am done.

61
00:03:04,701 --> 00:03:06,033
I'm done feeling guilty,

62
00:03:06,102 --> 00:03:08,814
and I am done measuring my
accomplishments against yours.

63
00:03:08,838 --> 00:03:10,372
I won't do it anymore.

64
00:03:10,440 --> 00:03:11,856
Just stay out of my way.

65
00:03:11,925 --> 00:03:12,957
Wow.

66
00:03:13,026 --> 00:03:14,586
You sound just like your mother.

67
00:03:16,847 --> 00:03:19,264
What happened to you?
Listen to me, Meredith.

68
00:03:19,333 --> 00:03:22,734
Anyone can fall in love
and be blindly happy,

69
00:03:22,802 --> 00:03:25,765
but not everyone can pick
up a scalpel and save a life.

70
00:03:25,789 --> 00:03:28,757
I raised you to be an
extraordinary human being.

71
00:03:28,825 --> 00:03:31,488
So imagine my disappointment
when I wake up after five years

72
00:03:31,512 --> 00:03:33,912
and discover that you're
no more than ordinary.

73
00:03:35,064 --> 00:03:36,304
What happened to you?

74
00:03:39,986 --> 00:03:41,720
This is crazy.

75
00:03:42,623 --> 00:03:44,856
It has to stop.

76
00:03:44,924 --> 00:03:47,503
I didn't hear you complaining
a few minutes ago.

77
00:03:47,527 --> 00:03:50,172
I heard something. I
wouldn't call it complaining.

78
00:03:50,196 --> 00:03:51,863
We're gonna get caught.

79
00:03:52,932 --> 00:03:55,133
We've had so many
close calls already.

80
00:03:57,471 --> 00:03:59,837
Is what we're doing so wrong?

81
00:03:59,906 --> 00:04:01,406
Don't be naive.

82
00:04:01,475 --> 00:04:04,943
Seattle's a small city with
a small-town mentality.

83
00:04:05,011 --> 00:04:06,961
So let's leave Seattle.

84
00:04:07,031 --> 00:04:09,297
Richard, you
deserve to be happy.

85
00:04:23,664 --> 00:04:25,363
What? Nothing.

86
00:04:25,432 --> 00:04:27,933
Just surprised to see you here.

87
00:04:28,002 --> 00:04:29,668
I'm working here.

88
00:04:29,737 --> 00:04:30,777
Oh.

89
00:04:32,138 --> 00:04:35,474
What? Nothing.
That's great. Just, um...

90
00:04:35,542 --> 00:04:37,787
Well, I thought Bailey
won the board seat.

91
00:04:37,811 --> 00:04:39,010
She did.

92
00:04:39,079 --> 00:04:40,999
They hired me back as
a peds surgery attending.

93
00:04:41,047 --> 00:04:43,081
Oh. That's great.

94
00:04:43,149 --> 00:04:45,567
That's really good.
That's awesome for you.

95
00:04:45,635 --> 00:04:47,297
Congratulations, man.
Okay, you know what?

96
00:04:47,321 --> 00:04:49,153
Shut it. I am a great surgeon.

97
00:04:49,222 --> 00:04:51,184
It's not like they're doing me
a favor. I'm doing them a favor.

98
00:04:51,208 --> 00:04:54,008
Besides, Robbins told me
that board vote was very close.

99
00:04:54,945 --> 00:04:57,028
Okay. Of course.

100
00:04:58,181 --> 00:05:00,631
What? Nothing. Just...

101
00:05:03,303 --> 00:05:05,837
I will assign you to
impacted bowels for a month.

102
00:05:05,906 --> 00:05:07,772
They'll call you Pooper Scooper.

103
00:05:08,809 --> 00:05:11,209
Robbins told Bailey
it was unanimous.

104
00:05:14,348 --> 00:05:15,580
Robbins.

105
00:05:15,649 --> 00:05:16,826
Ah! There you are.
Hey, welcome back.

106
00:05:16,850 --> 00:05:18,049
Can I talk to you?

107
00:05:18,118 --> 00:05:19,329
Yeah. Marty Secord in 2313.

108
00:05:19,353 --> 00:05:21,231
His liver enzymes
are looking good,

109
00:05:21,255 --> 00:05:22,915
but I'm worried he might
have to go back in for an ERCP,

110
00:05:22,939 --> 00:05:24,617
so you make sure
you keep an eye on it.

111
00:05:24,641 --> 00:05:26,186
I hear you, Dr. Herman.
Give me two minutes.

112
00:05:26,210 --> 00:05:27,454
God, you have no
idea how lucky you were

113
00:05:27,478 --> 00:05:28,921
to have me as a teacher
during your fellowship.

114
00:05:28,945 --> 00:05:31,073
We have to talk. One minute.

115
00:05:31,097 --> 00:05:33,114
My God, I am coming.

116
00:05:33,182 --> 00:05:36,384
Oh, no. No. Bummer.

117
00:05:37,621 --> 00:05:39,382
Wait. Maggie Pierce is quitting?

118
00:05:39,406 --> 00:05:40,772
I know. I'm into it.

119
00:05:40,841 --> 00:05:42,485
Avery, tell me I'm not
losing another cardio chief.

120
00:05:42,509 --> 00:05:44,770
I am into it, all right? My
mother's already called me twice.

121
00:05:44,794 --> 00:05:46,745
It's a PR nightmare.

122
00:05:46,797 --> 00:05:49,225
She's damn right it is. First
Russell, then Yang, now Pierce?

123
00:05:49,249 --> 00:05:51,266
Yang and I busted our
asses interviewing people,

124
00:05:51,334 --> 00:05:53,279
and now I have to start
this whole process over?

125
00:05:53,303 --> 00:05:55,615
Evidently, because it looks
like we hire from week to week.

126
00:05:55,639 --> 00:05:58,218
We're a revolving door.
Hey, you heard about Pierce?

127
00:05:58,242 --> 00:06:00,942
Yeah, I just read the e-mail.
Well, what should we do?

128
00:06:01,011 --> 00:06:02,477
I don't see anything we can do.

129
00:06:03,780 --> 00:06:06,460
I mean, we should
talk to her. Not me.

130
00:06:07,334 --> 00:06:10,151
Okay, I didn't mean
you! I meant all of us!

131
00:06:10,220 --> 00:06:12,320
We should get the
whole board together,

132
00:06:12,388 --> 00:06:13,855
do a full-court press.

133
00:06:13,924 --> 00:06:15,217
Uh, yeah, yeah.
You spearhead that.

134
00:06:15,241 --> 00:06:16,775
Well, I will.

135
00:06:16,844 --> 00:06:20,428
Lucky for you, the board just
got a transfusion of new blood.

136
00:06:20,497 --> 00:06:23,614
Maybe I could keep this place
from looking like a clown car.

137
00:06:23,683 --> 00:06:25,116
Maggie Pierce cannot quit.

138
00:06:26,453 --> 00:06:28,203
You cannot quit.

139
00:06:28,271 --> 00:06:31,239
Uh-huh. Word's out.
How you feeling, Roy?

140
00:06:31,308 --> 00:06:32,807
I like this mattress.

141
00:06:32,876 --> 00:06:35,036
I got to get me one of these.

142
00:06:35,378 --> 00:06:38,329
Mine is all foofy.

143
00:06:38,398 --> 00:06:39,709
We will see what we can do.

144
00:06:39,733 --> 00:06:41,093
What is this about
you resigning?

145
00:06:41,117 --> 00:06:43,413
Graft's deployed.
Let's inject the dye.

146
00:06:43,437 --> 00:06:45,753
Will you at least tell
me why you're leaving?

147
00:06:45,823 --> 00:06:49,741
That is between me and
my employer, Dr. Shepherd.

148
00:06:49,810 --> 00:06:52,850
I'm seeing diminished
perfusion to the spine.

149
00:06:54,597 --> 00:06:56,965
Roy, wiggle your toes
for me, would you, please?

150
00:06:57,985 --> 00:06:59,434
Wiggle, wiggle, wiggle.

151
00:07:01,404 --> 00:07:02,871
Like that?

152
00:07:02,939 --> 00:07:04,350
Wiggle a little harder.

153
00:07:04,374 --> 00:07:05,974
Let me check his
Babinski reflex.

154
00:07:08,478 --> 00:07:10,807
When the toes fan out
reflexively, what's that indicate?

155
00:07:10,831 --> 00:07:12,975
Just what you're afraid
of. High spinal injury.

156
00:07:12,999 --> 00:07:15,078
Is he paralyzed? Try it again.

157
00:07:15,102 --> 00:07:16,952
Something's wrong?

158
00:07:17,020 --> 00:07:19,504
I can't feel my legs.
What's happening?

159
00:07:19,573 --> 00:07:21,706
Roy, it's possible that
the blood to your spine

160
00:07:21,774 --> 00:07:23,135
has been cut off by the graft,

161
00:07:23,159 --> 00:07:25,726
but I'm gonna do everything
I can to fix it, okay?

162
00:07:25,795 --> 00:07:29,397
Okay. Please do. Please.

163
00:07:29,466 --> 00:07:31,243
I'm gonna give you
something to let you sleep.

164
00:07:31,267 --> 00:07:32,962
Start with trying to
induce hypertension.

165
00:07:32,986 --> 00:07:35,420
See if we can enhance
spinal perfusion.

166
00:07:37,040 --> 00:07:39,052
Did you get Maggie
Pierce's e-mail?

167
00:07:39,076 --> 00:07:41,542
I did, yes.

168
00:07:41,611 --> 00:07:44,011
Are you going to
talk to her again?

169
00:07:44,063 --> 00:07:47,482
She won't listen.
She doesn't trust me.

170
00:07:47,551 --> 00:07:50,836
She's angry I didn't
tell her sooner. So am I.

171
00:07:50,904 --> 00:07:53,699
I just still can't even remember
my mother being pregnant.

172
00:07:53,723 --> 00:07:56,590
I just... I need that journal
from the spring of '83.

173
00:07:56,659 --> 00:07:57,899
Do you have that one?

174
00:07:57,928 --> 00:08:00,494
Yeah, I have them here.

175
00:08:00,563 --> 00:08:02,897
I mean, we both looked
at them a hundred times.

176
00:08:02,966 --> 00:08:04,833
It's mostly surgical stuff.

177
00:08:04,901 --> 00:08:06,445
Can you just dig it
out for me, please?

178
00:08:06,469 --> 00:08:07,868
Okay.

179
00:08:08,771 --> 00:08:11,322
Help! Can you help, please?

180
00:08:11,391 --> 00:08:12,835
Come with me. What happened?

181
00:08:12,859 --> 00:08:14,453
I was just dropping my
friend off when I saw her here.

182
00:08:14,477 --> 00:08:16,611
She was lying.
She was all alone.

183
00:08:16,679 --> 00:08:19,625
Run inside and tell
someone I need a gurney!

184
00:08:20,817 --> 00:08:22,466
Honey, I'm a doctor.

185
00:08:22,535 --> 00:08:23,912
What's your name? Nadia.

186
00:08:23,936 --> 00:08:25,598
Nadia, tell me where it hurts.

187
00:08:25,622 --> 00:08:27,222
Everywhere.

188
00:08:28,658 --> 00:08:29,707
Oh, God.

189
00:08:52,699 --> 00:08:54,683
This is insane. Is she laboring?

190
00:08:54,751 --> 00:08:57,168
Her pressure's
really low, 78 over 45.

191
00:08:57,237 --> 00:08:59,687
Let's get her a
600cc fluid bolus.

192
00:08:59,756 --> 00:09:02,490
Nadia, Nadia, how
far along are you?

193
00:09:02,559 --> 00:09:04,359
Ten. Ten months?

194
00:09:04,428 --> 00:09:05,621
She's saying she's 10 years old.

195
00:09:05,645 --> 00:09:07,106
She doesn't know what
you're talking about.

196
00:09:07,130 --> 00:09:09,250
Rigid abdomen with
generalized tenderness.

197
00:09:09,299 --> 00:09:11,266
Edwards, let's
get the ultrasound.

198
00:09:11,335 --> 00:09:12,900
Nadia, where are your parents?

199
00:09:12,970 --> 00:09:14,280
If she has a mother,
where the hell's her mother?

200
00:09:14,304 --> 00:09:16,304
Oh, she should be in prison.

201
00:09:16,807 --> 00:09:19,323
Nadia, I need you to sit still.

202
00:09:19,376 --> 00:09:22,360
I know. I know. I
just need to see if...

203
00:09:23,480 --> 00:09:24,879
Just needed to see...

204
00:09:28,001 --> 00:09:29,241
Okay. Okay.

205
00:09:30,036 --> 00:09:31,036
What?

206
00:09:31,104 --> 00:09:32,970
She's not pregnant.
It's not a baby.

207
00:09:33,039 --> 00:09:35,473
Looks like a mass,
and there's free fluid.

208
00:09:35,542 --> 00:09:37,775
Oh, thank God.
That was getting dark.

209
00:09:39,813 --> 00:09:42,847
A mass the size of a
soccer ball is still pretty dark.

210
00:09:42,916 --> 00:09:44,076
Okay, forget the CT.

211
00:09:44,100 --> 00:09:46,267
She's hypotensive
with peritonitis.

212
00:09:46,336 --> 00:09:47,618
This mass may have ruptured.

213
00:09:47,671 --> 00:09:48,781
We really should
get her up to the OR.

214
00:09:48,805 --> 00:09:50,238
I'll call up.

215
00:09:50,323 --> 00:09:52,668
And then let's call the police
and Child Protective Services.

216
00:09:52,692 --> 00:09:54,771
Letting your kid get this
sick and then abandoning her

217
00:09:54,795 --> 00:09:56,515
is still child abuse. Okay.

218
00:09:57,597 --> 00:09:59,164
Amy, what do you need?

219
00:09:59,232 --> 00:10:00,809
On three. One, two, three.

220
00:10:00,833 --> 00:10:02,178
Looks like paralysis caused

221
00:10:02,202 --> 00:10:03,462
by SCI during a TEVAR procedure.

222
00:10:03,486 --> 00:10:04,930
I've induced hypertension

223
00:10:04,954 --> 00:10:06,332
and adjusted the
stent to alleviate,

224
00:10:06,356 --> 00:10:07,499
but nothing has worked.

225
00:10:07,523 --> 00:10:08,951
He needs immediate
spinal cord drainage.

226
00:10:08,975 --> 00:10:10,519
You're here. Why do you need me?

227
00:10:10,543 --> 00:10:12,910
I have stuff to do. I
thought you could take it.

228
00:10:12,980 --> 00:10:14,879
Perks of being chief of neuro.

229
00:10:14,948 --> 00:10:17,298
And this might be your
last chance to work together.

230
00:10:17,367 --> 00:10:18,567
I was just telling Dr. Pierce

231
00:10:18,635 --> 00:10:20,579
why I thought her departure
was such a bad idea.

232
00:10:20,603 --> 00:10:22,203
I know, right?

233
00:10:22,272 --> 00:10:25,073
I thought you've been here longer
than I have, you and Meredith.

234
00:10:25,142 --> 00:10:28,176
Thought maybe you could talk
about it. Derek's easy to talk to.

235
00:10:28,245 --> 00:10:31,730
You can tell him
anything. Anything.

236
00:10:34,333 --> 00:10:36,333
Gown and glove, please.

237
00:10:36,402 --> 00:10:38,547
Don't you have stuff to do?

238
00:10:38,571 --> 00:10:40,838
Yes. Good luck. Good talk.

239
00:10:43,793 --> 00:10:45,404
The Journal of
American Medicine!

240
00:10:45,428 --> 00:10:46,878
<i>Unbelievable.</i>

241
00:10:46,930 --> 00:10:48,729
What's not to
believe? The method.

242
00:10:48,798 --> 00:10:52,010
You're calling... You actually
named it the Grey Method?

243
00:10:52,034 --> 00:10:54,802
Well, what else am I
gonna call it? It's my name.

244
00:10:54,871 --> 00:10:57,555
It's a little audacious.

245
00:10:57,624 --> 00:10:59,056
Is that it?

246
00:11:00,894 --> 00:11:03,544
Yeah. Spring of '83.

247
00:11:03,613 --> 00:11:04,990
Is there anything in there?

248
00:11:05,014 --> 00:11:06,814
There's some
surgical notes, ideas.

249
00:11:06,883 --> 00:11:08,966
Maybe you'll see
something. I didn't.

250
00:11:09,035 --> 00:11:11,475
I have a surgery.
Thanks for this.

251
00:11:12,339 --> 00:11:14,016
We need to talk
about Maggie Pierce.

252
00:11:14,040 --> 00:11:15,506
Bailey...

253
00:11:15,575 --> 00:11:18,393
The e-mail said, "For
professional and personal reasons."

254
00:11:18,462 --> 00:11:19,860
Now, you know
what that could be?

255
00:11:19,929 --> 00:11:21,774
Why would I?
Well, you talk to her.

256
00:11:21,798 --> 00:11:24,544
Bailey, she resigned. We
can't hold her against her will.

257
00:11:24,568 --> 00:11:26,000
I'm not saying that.

258
00:11:26,069 --> 00:11:29,070
I'm saying we change her will.

259
00:11:29,139 --> 00:11:31,573
I'm trying to get
the board together,

260
00:11:31,641 --> 00:11:34,125
but I think you
need to talk to her,

261
00:11:34,194 --> 00:11:37,211
like you used to talk to me,
you know, when I was first here

262
00:11:37,280 --> 00:11:39,380
and I didn't know my
ass from my elbow.

263
00:11:39,449 --> 00:11:40,965
I probably would have quit...

264
00:11:41,034 --> 00:11:42,967
Damn it, Bailey, she's leaving!

265
00:11:43,036 --> 00:11:46,316
I can't do anything
about it. Just let it go.

266
00:11:48,792 --> 00:11:50,369
Almost done
draining, Dr. Shepherd.

267
00:11:50,393 --> 00:11:51,904
You know, I'm just curious.

268
00:11:51,928 --> 00:11:55,274
Speaking as someone who
just had a pretty great job

269
00:11:55,298 --> 00:11:56,647
and then turned it down,

270
00:11:56,716 --> 00:12:00,434
I know a rash decision
can be pretty disastrous.

271
00:12:00,503 --> 00:12:02,620
Could we just call it a bad fit?

272
00:12:02,689 --> 00:12:05,468
We could if you'd been here
long enough to know that.

273
00:12:05,492 --> 00:12:06,541
It's not the job.

274
00:12:06,609 --> 00:12:07,849
Then what is it?

275
00:12:07,877 --> 00:12:09,694
I'm sure your wife has told you.

276
00:12:09,762 --> 00:12:11,262
How we doing?

277
00:12:11,331 --> 00:12:13,631
My wife? Told me what?

278
00:12:13,700 --> 00:12:15,149
Oh.

279
00:12:15,218 --> 00:12:17,080
Look, I know you
two have butted heads

280
00:12:17,104 --> 00:12:18,931
and she hasn't been welcoming.

281
00:12:18,955 --> 00:12:20,866
- To say the least.
- She's just one surgeon.

282
00:12:20,890 --> 00:12:22,818
Why don't you just, you
know, stay away from her

283
00:12:22,842 --> 00:12:25,402
- until you figure out...
- It's not as simple as...

284
00:12:27,230 --> 00:12:28,429
Oh, God.

285
00:12:29,232 --> 00:12:32,416
You don't know anything.

286
00:12:32,485 --> 00:12:34,447
I'm sorry. What's going on?

287
00:12:34,471 --> 00:12:36,303
You should talk to your wife.

288
00:12:36,372 --> 00:12:38,439
Yeah, okay. Let's
get him on his back.

289
00:12:38,508 --> 00:12:42,343
On three. One, two, three.

290
00:12:45,515 --> 00:12:47,835
Derek, Babinski reflex?

291
00:12:50,303 --> 00:12:52,069
Damn it.

292
00:12:52,138 --> 00:12:53,649
I'm sorry, Dr. Pierce.

293
00:12:53,673 --> 00:12:56,341
You did everything you
could, but this man is paralyzed.

294
00:13:05,402 --> 00:13:07,168
No.

295
00:13:07,237 --> 00:13:10,338
Nope. Prep for a sternotomy. I
need a bypass machine in here, stat.

296
00:13:10,407 --> 00:13:12,918
Wilson, go get his wife's
consent for an open-heart surgery.

297
00:13:12,942 --> 00:13:13,986
What are you planning on doing?

298
00:13:14,010 --> 00:13:15,693
I am going to fix it.

299
00:13:15,762 --> 00:13:16,661
You can help if you want,
but if you're not gonna help,

300
00:13:16,729 --> 00:13:18,079
I need you out of the way.

301
00:13:30,010 --> 00:13:31,092
<i>Mom?</i>

302
00:13:34,631 --> 00:13:35,646
<i>Mommy?</i>

303
00:13:35,715 --> 00:13:36,948
<i>Meredith.</i>

304
00:13:39,069 --> 00:13:40,245
You grew up.

305
00:13:40,269 --> 00:13:41,302
I did.

306
00:13:42,422 --> 00:13:44,755
It's a shame.

307
00:13:44,824 --> 00:13:47,458
It's awful being a grown-up.

308
00:13:47,527 --> 00:13:49,847
But the carousel
never stops turning.

309
00:13:51,498 --> 00:13:52,730
You can't get off.

310
00:13:56,252 --> 00:13:58,572
You page me? What do you got?

311
00:13:58,821 --> 00:14:00,254
Yeah.

312
00:14:00,323 --> 00:14:03,523
Do you remember the day you
met my mom at the carousel?

313
00:14:04,794 --> 00:14:06,227
What? That's what you...

314
00:14:06,296 --> 00:14:07,628
I remember this day.

315
00:14:07,696 --> 00:14:11,382
I was on the carousel at
the park and you came,

316
00:14:11,451 --> 00:14:14,797
and then you were arguing
and she said something to you.

317
00:14:14,821 --> 00:14:17,021
Do you remember what she said?

318
00:14:17,940 --> 00:14:21,208
Meredith, that was
a long time ago.

319
00:14:22,695 --> 00:14:24,562
I don't remember.

320
00:14:26,466 --> 00:14:28,165
Is that all you wanted?

321
00:14:29,135 --> 00:14:30,702
Yeah, I just thought...

322
00:14:33,873 --> 00:14:35,088
Forget it.

323
00:14:41,581 --> 00:14:43,276
I was thinking
about what you said,

324
00:14:43,300 --> 00:14:45,349
and it might be better for them,

325
00:14:45,418 --> 00:14:47,385
Thatcher and Adele, ultimately.

326
00:14:47,454 --> 00:14:48,797
Of course it would.

327
00:14:48,821 --> 00:14:51,033
Let them find people
who will make them happy.

328
00:14:51,057 --> 00:14:53,217
I never wanted to...

329
00:14:58,831 --> 00:15:00,598
I never wanted to cheat.

330
00:15:01,534 --> 00:15:03,368
I never imagined
myself a cheater.

331
00:15:03,436 --> 00:15:05,614
You have the power
to change that, Richard.

332
00:15:05,638 --> 00:15:07,471
It's in your hands.

333
00:15:07,540 --> 00:15:10,641
I've been ready to
do this for a long time.

334
00:15:10,710 --> 00:15:12,760
The question is, are you?

335
00:15:17,651 --> 00:15:19,183
The wife gave consent.

336
00:15:19,252 --> 00:15:21,530
That's lucky. I've been in
his chest for a while now.

337
00:15:21,554 --> 00:15:22,794
That was a bold bet.

338
00:15:22,855 --> 00:15:24,066
Wait. Is that an aneurysm sac?

339
00:15:24,090 --> 00:15:25,590
Did you just fix that?

340
00:15:25,659 --> 00:15:27,019
Yeah, but now I'm gonna
use it to bring blood back

341
00:15:27,043 --> 00:15:28,676
to the spinal cord.

342
00:15:28,744 --> 00:15:30,244
Wait. I'm lost.

343
00:15:30,313 --> 00:15:31,807
Yeah. I was, too, for a while.

344
00:15:31,831 --> 00:15:33,376
He is paralyzed
because his aorta

345
00:15:33,400 --> 00:15:34,910
isn't sending
blood to his spine.

346
00:15:34,934 --> 00:15:36,962
So I replaced the aorta
with a Dacron graft,

347
00:15:36,986 --> 00:15:40,237
and now I'm rebuilding the
aneurysm into a second aorta

348
00:15:40,306 --> 00:15:43,807
that will just send blood to the
spine, kind of like a side road.

349
00:15:43,876 --> 00:15:45,604
Is that... You can do that?

350
00:15:45,628 --> 00:15:47,305
Not many could, but she is.

351
00:15:47,329 --> 00:15:49,141
I can see why you
want to keep her around.

352
00:15:49,165 --> 00:15:52,600
Well, yeah, and... Never mind.

353
00:15:52,669 --> 00:15:53,845
And it'll work?

354
00:15:53,869 --> 00:15:54,919
God knows.

355
00:15:55,988 --> 00:15:57,888
It's a last-ditch effort.

356
00:15:57,957 --> 00:15:59,723
Take me with you when you go.

357
00:15:59,792 --> 00:16:02,826
Suction. And get
another 6-0 Prolene ready.

358
00:16:02,879 --> 00:16:05,646
Don't just stand
there, Wilson. Scrub in.

359
00:16:08,751 --> 00:16:11,518
Okay, the tumor has taken
over the abdominal cavity.

360
00:16:11,588 --> 00:16:13,365
It's pushed the viscera
over to one side.

361
00:16:13,389 --> 00:16:16,657
Let's debulk as much of
this mass as we can, en bloc,

362
00:16:16,726 --> 00:16:18,659
and when we get
closer to the organs,

363
00:16:18,728 --> 00:16:20,744
we can resect it piece by piece.

364
00:16:20,814 --> 00:16:21,829
Fine.

365
00:16:23,232 --> 00:16:24,232
What?

366
00:16:25,067 --> 00:16:26,333
Edwards told me.

367
00:16:26,402 --> 00:16:28,569
You guys were
unanimous for Bailey.

368
00:16:28,638 --> 00:16:29,953
Who told you that?

369
00:16:30,023 --> 00:16:31,833
Dr. Bailey. Why
would she do that?

370
00:16:31,857 --> 00:16:33,007
I kind of had her back.

371
00:16:33,075 --> 00:16:34,386
And you should have had mine.

372
00:16:34,410 --> 00:16:35,838
You listened to my speech.
You said it was good.

373
00:16:35,862 --> 00:16:37,473
It was good. Then
what the hell, then?

374
00:16:37,497 --> 00:16:39,375
Bailey's was better.
Oh, that's great.

375
00:16:39,399 --> 00:16:41,866
Alex, you would make
a fine board member,

376
00:16:41,934 --> 00:16:44,635
but Bailey will make
an exceptional one.

377
00:16:44,703 --> 00:16:46,637
Is that what you want me to do?

378
00:16:46,705 --> 00:16:48,873
Vote for you to be
good, to be fine?

379
00:16:48,941 --> 00:16:51,642
You want my pity
vote? I wouldn't.

380
00:16:59,552 --> 00:17:01,486
Have you lightened sedation?

381
00:17:01,554 --> 00:17:03,754
Okay. He is coming around.

382
00:17:03,823 --> 00:17:05,289
Want to do the honors?

383
00:17:06,893 --> 00:17:09,710
Roy. Roy, are you with us?

384
00:17:11,147 --> 00:17:12,975
Roy, you're okay.
The surgery is all done.

385
00:17:12,999 --> 00:17:15,566
I just need you to
wiggle your toes for me.

386
00:17:15,635 --> 00:17:17,035
Can you do that?

387
00:17:20,523 --> 00:17:22,051
Roy, wiggle your toes, okay?

388
00:17:23,276 --> 00:17:25,192
Roy, wiggle your toes.

389
00:17:30,649 --> 00:17:32,209
Unbelievable.

390
00:17:32,267 --> 00:17:34,713
All right, get him sedated
and get him up to recovery.

391
00:17:34,737 --> 00:17:37,821
And good work,
everybody. Thank you, all.

392
00:17:37,890 --> 00:17:40,469
She keeps saying talk to my
wife. Do you know what she means?

393
00:17:40,493 --> 00:17:41,592
I might.

394
00:17:41,661 --> 00:17:42,693
Well?

395
00:17:42,762 --> 00:17:45,396
But I'm not talking
about anything

396
00:17:45,465 --> 00:17:48,966
I might have learned
in AA about someone.

397
00:17:49,935 --> 00:17:51,969
Because I made a pledge there.

398
00:17:52,037 --> 00:17:55,790
But someone else might
know what I can't talk about.

399
00:17:55,859 --> 00:17:57,099
Is Pierce in AA?

400
00:17:57,126 --> 00:17:58,292
No. No!

401
00:17:58,361 --> 00:18:00,544
So you should
definitely talk to her.

402
00:18:00,613 --> 00:18:01,790
She'll just say talk to my wife.

403
00:18:01,814 --> 00:18:03,454
Then you should
talk to your wife.

404
00:18:05,184 --> 00:18:07,064
Edwards, you ready? Uh-huh.

405
00:18:08,721 --> 00:18:10,499
It's invading everything.

406
00:18:10,523 --> 00:18:12,173
I'm literally peeling
it off the spleen.

407
00:18:12,242 --> 00:18:15,543
And 7.8 pounds. Wow.

408
00:18:15,611 --> 00:18:17,822
7.8 pounds of lousy parenting.

409
00:18:17,846 --> 00:18:19,575
But she does have a Dutch braid.

410
00:18:19,599 --> 00:18:21,843
It's like a French one
but only harder to do.

411
00:18:21,867 --> 00:18:23,912
I used to do it for my sister
when my mom was strung out.

412
00:18:23,936 --> 00:18:25,580
It took me an hour,
and it still fell apart.

413
00:18:25,604 --> 00:18:27,471
Only a saint or her mother

414
00:18:27,540 --> 00:18:30,624
would take the time to
do something like this.

415
00:18:30,693 --> 00:18:33,127
You need an extra set of hands?

416
00:18:33,195 --> 00:18:35,947
No, we're good. Thanks. Metz?

417
00:18:36,015 --> 00:18:38,177
She takes the time to
do her daughter's hair.

418
00:18:38,201 --> 00:18:40,329
How the hell does she let
her develop an 8-pound tumor?

419
00:18:40,353 --> 00:18:43,070
You and I know something
about crazy mothers.

420
00:18:43,139 --> 00:18:45,423
Be careful. It's impinging
on the left hepatic vein.

421
00:18:45,491 --> 00:18:46,602
I see it.

422
00:18:48,544 --> 00:18:49,560
Damn it.

423
00:18:55,601 --> 00:18:57,929
Where are you?
Where are you? Got it!

424
00:18:57,953 --> 00:18:59,431
She's bleeding
out from her liver.

425
00:18:59,455 --> 00:19:00,699
I'm packing, but
I can't control it.

426
00:19:00,723 --> 00:19:02,017
More laps. Hang
another unit of blood?

427
00:19:02,041 --> 00:19:03,135
Right away.

428
00:19:03,159 --> 00:19:04,619
Edwards, more suction.

429
00:19:04,643 --> 00:19:06,322
<i>I said clamp, now!</i>

430
00:19:06,346 --> 00:19:07,889
- Another.
- Another.

431
00:19:07,913 --> 00:19:09,125
One bullet went
through the right

432
00:19:09,149 --> 00:19:10,676
lower quadrant and
perfed the colon.

433
00:19:10,700 --> 00:19:12,661
A penetrating injury to the
liver here. I need more laps!

434
00:19:12,685 --> 00:19:14,863
She's crashing. We got
to stop this bleed. Suction.

435
00:19:14,887 --> 00:19:15,953
Come on. Come on!

436
00:19:16,022 --> 00:19:17,433
Bokhee, 4-0 silk for ligation.

437
00:19:20,260 --> 00:19:22,100
It's not working.
We're gonna lose her.

438
00:19:23,629 --> 00:19:24,840
What about a balloon tamponade?

439
00:19:24,864 --> 00:19:27,081
What? A balloon tamponade.

440
00:19:27,150 --> 00:19:30,984
That could control a
penetrating liver injury. It should.

441
00:19:31,053 --> 00:19:32,497
Yes. Get me a Foley catheter.

442
00:19:32,521 --> 00:19:34,066
You might need more...
More than one. I know.

443
00:19:34,090 --> 00:19:36,173
Foley, now. Let's go.

444
00:19:38,744 --> 00:19:40,055
You think that'll
hold the bleed?

445
00:19:40,079 --> 00:19:41,573
It's the best chance we've got.

446
00:19:41,597 --> 00:19:43,030
Bokhee, clamp.

447
00:19:56,862 --> 00:19:58,942
Inflating the balloon.

448
00:20:06,189 --> 00:20:09,757
I'll be damned.
Nice work, Dr. Grey.

449
00:20:09,825 --> 00:20:11,509
BP's climbing.

450
00:20:15,682 --> 00:20:18,349
That's amazing. How the
hell did you think of that?

451
00:20:21,387 --> 00:20:22,627
I don't know.

452
00:20:23,806 --> 00:20:25,422
You okay?

453
00:20:25,491 --> 00:20:27,391
She's fine. You
saved her. She's fine.

454
00:20:27,460 --> 00:20:28,992
Yeah, I'm okay.

455
00:20:36,585 --> 00:20:38,413
There's never
gonna be a good time.

456
00:20:38,437 --> 00:20:41,717
We just have to do it
quickly, rip off the bandage.

457
00:20:43,409 --> 00:20:46,610
I'll tell Adele. Tonight.

458
00:20:49,482 --> 00:20:50,864
I'll tell Thatcher.

459
00:20:53,135 --> 00:20:54,579
My heart's racing.
We're really gonna...

460
00:20:54,603 --> 00:20:55,981
Dr. Grey?

461
00:20:56,005 --> 00:20:58,005
Excuse me. Dr. Grey? One minute!

462
00:20:59,258 --> 00:21:00,391
Yes, Chief?

463
00:21:00,460 --> 00:21:01,520
Sorry, Dr. Grey.

464
00:21:01,544 --> 00:21:04,044
I just received a very
interesting phone call.

465
00:21:04,113 --> 00:21:06,847
Your lap method, the
one you just published.

466
00:21:06,916 --> 00:21:08,315
The Grey Method.

467
00:21:08,384 --> 00:21:10,434
The Grey Method, yes.

468
00:21:10,503 --> 00:21:12,731
It's just been placed on
the short list of nominations

469
00:21:12,755 --> 00:21:15,556
for the Harper Avery award.

470
00:21:16,608 --> 00:21:18,809
Are you... It is?
Are you kidding?

471
00:21:18,877 --> 00:21:23,130
No surgical resident has
ever made that list before.

472
00:21:23,198 --> 00:21:26,718
I only hope we can convince
you to stay in Seattle.

473
00:21:26,752 --> 00:21:28,363
Well, that's very... No, I know.

474
00:21:28,387 --> 00:21:30,604
You'll have your
veritable pick after this.

475
00:21:32,041 --> 00:21:34,041
Very well done, Grey.

476
00:21:34,110 --> 00:21:36,594
Oh, the board would
like to see you to...

477
00:21:36,663 --> 00:21:37,928
Of course.

478
00:21:47,990 --> 00:21:49,923
Meredith. Derek, not now.

479
00:21:49,992 --> 00:21:52,409
Five minutes. Just five minutes.

480
00:21:52,478 --> 00:21:54,289
Derek, I swear to God,
I can't do this right now.

481
00:21:54,313 --> 00:21:56,447
I am sorry about the thing
I said about your mother.

482
00:21:56,516 --> 00:21:59,244
Why? You meant it. It was
in the heat of the moment.

483
00:21:59,268 --> 00:22:01,012
You know, you wanted to
hurt me, and you did that,

484
00:22:01,036 --> 00:22:03,115
so at least have the
guts to stand by it.

485
00:22:03,139 --> 00:22:04,254
Will you just hear me out?

486
00:22:04,323 --> 00:22:05,433
You could do worse
than compare me

487
00:22:05,457 --> 00:22:06,923
to a brilliant surgeon,

488
00:22:06,992 --> 00:22:09,171
but you meant it in the sense
that I am cold and ambitious

489
00:22:09,195 --> 00:22:12,329
and selfish, a horrible
wife and mother. I got that.

490
00:22:12,398 --> 00:22:14,965
I love how you just switch it
around so you can make it fit.

491
00:22:15,034 --> 00:22:17,913
You think I sound like
my mother? You do.

492
00:22:17,937 --> 00:22:21,705
And now I get to live under the
weight of your disappointment, too?

493
00:22:21,774 --> 00:22:23,435
Because of
something you gave up.

494
00:22:23,459 --> 00:22:25,025
If you recall, I
gave it up for you.

495
00:22:25,094 --> 00:22:27,578
Oh, you gave it up for
me, but I don't want it.

496
00:22:27,647 --> 00:22:30,397
Go. You should get
on the next flight out.

497
00:22:30,466 --> 00:22:33,768
Call the President and
get the job back. Just go.

498
00:23:23,352 --> 00:23:25,886
Blood. It's just blood.

499
00:23:29,408 --> 00:23:32,926
Meredith, don't be
afraid. Don't be afraid.

500
00:23:44,740 --> 00:23:46,451
<i>911. What's your emergency?</i>

